[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can now generate AI videos natively in 4K, but how does it compare in terms of price and quality? I have a consistent character workflow that I think does better than most other AI character workflows that I\'ve seen up to'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this point, [music] and we\'re taking an honest look at the AI video generator Happy Horse. We have all of that and more in today\'s episode of AI Film News. So, saddle up and let\'s get to it.'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Before we get going, I want to give a hat tip to everyone in the Curious Refuge community who attended our freelancing animation and screenwriting office hours that we hosted this last week. It was really fun, and we'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'appreciate all of the fascinating questions that were presented in those live streams that you can find over in our community. Okay, so let\'s get to the news. So, the first bit of news that I want to talk about comes from the folks at Kling. So, Kling actually came out'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the ability for you to generate AI videos natively in 4K. The reason why this is important is because most other AI video generation tools that are out there only generate natively in 720p or'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '1080p. The problem is when you\'re ready to distribute that AI video in 4K or beyond, it can kind of go through a lot of detail loss, and so you typically'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would have to use an AI video up reser to convert from 1080 to 4K. But, often times there was a quality loss. So, the value proposition really is if you have the ability to generate natively in 4K, you will have all of the rich details'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that sometimes get lost whenever you up res from 1080 into 4K or beyond. But, I don\'t want you to take my word for it. Let\'s hop into the tools and see for ourselves. Now, to generate your footage in 4K, you can use any aggregator of'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your choice, or you can just go over to Kling directly. For this example, I\'m going to hop into Magnific. And if that sounds funny, it\'s because Magnific actually is the new name of Freepik.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s funny, Freepik acquired Magnific recently and then decided to change their name to Magnific. So, anytime you hear FreePik, assume that we\'re actually talking about Magnific going forward. Okay, so I\'m inside the video generation'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'section and I have this quick little image here of this man inside of a coffee shop, just a very standard shot that you would see inside a film project. We\'ll go ahead and drag and drop that to our start image section'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here and then I have a quick little prompt prompting for him to say a quick line and then you can see down here you have the ability to select 4K and also the duration of [music] the video clip.'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And of course, we\'re going to have sound turned on and when you\'re ready, go ahead and hit generate. So, here\'s a similar generation in 1080p. Again, this is not up-res\'d. I think this is the best cup of tea I\'ve'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ever had. Okay, you get the idea and then here is the same image and prompt in 4K. &gt;&gt; [snorts] &gt;&gt; I think this is the best cup of tea I\'ve ever had. Okay, robotic delivery and breaking the fourth wall aside, I think'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the resolution and the fidelity in the 4K version is just light-years better. And it\'s not hyper-sharpening the edges, it actually is staying true to the integrity of what you would hope'

